@Node "Machine requirements" "ImageStudio.guide/Machine requirements"
@Next "Brief description"
@Prev "Copyright and Disclaimer"
@Toc "Introduction"

Machine requirements
====================

   ImageStudio requires the following system to run:

   @{b}*@{ub} Workbench 2.04 or above.

   @{b}*@{ub} Around 1 megabyte of free memory.

   @{b}*@{ub} Several megabytes of free hard disk space.

   If ImageStudio is run on an AGA machine (A1200 or A4000), it will
use the new display modes and palette routines to improve the quality
of the internal viewer images.


@EndNode

@Node "Brief description" "ImageStudio.guide/Brief description"
@Next "List of features"
@Prev "Machine requirements"
@Toc "Introduction"

Brief description
=================

   ImageStudio is written for the casual graphics user who wishes to
convert or manipulate various graphics formats on a modest Amiga
system. There are several commercial offerings available, however the
casual user is paying a lot of money for many facilities and options
they would probably never use.

   Bitmap graphics, by their nature, usually require large amounts of
RAM. One of the main objectives of ImageStudio was to reduce this
burden by utilising virtual memory - most users have more spare hard
disk space than spare RAM.

   ImageStudio works with several buffers at any one time (dependant on
how many levels of undo are specified), each of these buffers can hold
either colour-mapped or 24-bit images. For a detailed description of
colour-mapped and 24-bit images, See @{"Image types" Link "Image types"}.

   ImageStudio comes with a fully featured ARexx port, which allows the
writing of macro scripts to automate repetative processes and also
allows communication with other ARexx aware programs. Again, ARexx has
the reputation of being "something pretty difficult", so we've
simplified the use of ARexx in ImageStudio by allowing the user to
create, edit and run scripts entirely within ImageStudio - ImageStudio
even provides a blank template as a starting point for each new script.


@EndNode

@Node "List of features" "ImageStudio.guide/List of features"
@Next "Shareware version"
@Prev "Brief description"
@Toc "Introduction"

List of features
================

   General:
   @{b}*@{ub} Full 24-bit image buffers, with optimizations for colour-mapped
     (palette based) images.

   @{b}*@{ub} Up to 100 levels of undo / redo.

   @{b}*@{ub} User configurable virtual memory.

   @{b}*@{ub} Fully featured, easy to use, ARexx interface.

   @{b}*@{ub} Fully font sensitive, style guide complient, user interface.

   @{b}*@{ub} Fully CyberGraphX compatibility for both the viewers and the
     preview window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Modular loaders and savers.

   @{b}*@{ub} User saveable preferences.

   @{b}*@{ub} Operations applicable to the whole image or a selected region.

   @{b}*@{ub} Up to 256 greyshade preview window (with optional dither).

   @{b}*@{ub} Zoom on preview window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Internal / external viewers.

   @{b}*@{ub} Loading / saving / manipulating of AGA image formats (e.g. 256
     colours, HAM8) on non-AGA machines.

   @{b}*@{ub} Max image size of 32000 x 32000 (crops images to 512 x 512 in the
     unregistered version).

   @{b}*@{ub} Copy / paste to / from the system clipboard.

   @{b}*@{ub} Runs on all Workbench 2.04+ Amiga's - utilises AGA chipset if
     available.

   @{b}*@{ub} Online AmigaGuide help, as well as ASCII, TeX @{b}.dvi@{ub} and PostScript
     documentation.

   @{b}*@{ub} Multi-level help error requesters.

   @{b}*@{ub} Public screen.

   @{b}*@{ub} Requires no third party libraries or utilities.

   Import:
   @{b}*@{ub} IFF-ILBM formats (Standard palette based, HAM6, HAM8, extra half
     bright, ILBM24)

   @{b}*@{ub} BMP

   @{b}*@{ub} Datatypes (with Workbench3.0 and above)

   @{b}*@{ub} GIF (conforming to GIF87a or GIF89a)

   @{b}*@{ub} IFF-DEEP

   @{b}*@{ub} JPEG (conforming to JFIF standard)

   @{b}*@{ub} PCX

   @{b}*@{ub} PNM (PBM, PGM, PPM, ASCII and binary)

   @{b}*@{ub} QRT (DKB, POV)

   @{b}*@{ub} SGI

   @{b}*@{ub} Targa

   @{b}*@{ub} TIFF

   @{b}*@{ub} VMEM (internal virtual memory format)

   Export:
   @{b}*@{ub} IFF-ILBM formats (Standard palette based, HAM6, HAM8, extra half
     bright, ILBM24)

   @{b}*@{ub} BMP

   @{b}*@{ub} EPS

   @{b}*@{ub} GIF (conforming to GIF87a or GIF89a)

   @{b}*@{ub} IFF-DEEP

   @{b}*@{ub} JPEG (conforming to JFIF standard)

   @{b}*@{ub} PCX

   @{b}*@{ub} PNM (PBM, PGM, PPM, ASCII and binary)

   @{b}*@{ub} QRT (DKB, POV)

   @{b}*@{ub} SGI

   @{b}*@{ub} Targa

   @{b}*@{ub} TIFF

   @{b}*@{ub} VMEM (internal virtual memory format)

   Colour Balance:
   @{b}*@{ub} All operations are available to the R,G,B components separately.

   @{b}*@{ub} Brightness ( upto ±100%)

   @{b}*@{ub} Contrast (non to full)

   @{b}*@{ub} Gamma ( + and - )

   Convolution:
   @{b}*@{ub} Many supplied convolution filters.

   @{b}*@{ub} User definable convolutions, load and save to disk.

   Effects:
   @{b}*@{ub} Built in effects: Dynamic range expansion, FlipX, FlipY, RollX,
     RollY, Negative, Greyscale, Highlight, Shadow, Random, Pixelize,
     Remove isolated pixels.

   Scale:
   @{b}*@{ub} Crop to selected region.

   @{b}*@{ub} Increase / decrease scale by percentage or absolute image size.

   @{b}*@{ub} Simple scale or colour averaged.

   Colour reduction:
   @{b}*@{ub} Increase colour mapped images to 24-bit.

   @{b}*@{ub} Decrease number of colours in 24-bit or colour mapped images via
     Heckbert median cut algorithm.

   @{b}*@{ub} Dithers available for colour reduction: None, Floyd-Steinberg,
     Burkes, Stucki, Sierra, Jarvis, Stevenson-Arce.

   Palette:
   @{b}*@{ub} Edit palette colours and ranges.

   @{b}*@{ub} Save current palette.

   @{b}*@{ub} Force palette onto current image, dithering if necessary (all dith
     ers available).


@EndNode

